\section{Homework assignments}

\paragraph{Assignment format.} The homework assignment will be distributed as an R Markdown document; see \href{https://github.com/Katsevich-Teaching/stat-471-fall-2021/blob/main/homework/homework-0/homework-0.Rmd}{homework-0.Rmd} for an example. This format facilitates the integration of code, results, and prose, producing a PDF report; see \href{https://github.com/Katsevich-Teaching/stat-471-fall-2021/blob/main/homework/homework-0/homework-0.pdf}{homework-0.pdf} for an example. Read more about Rmd format \href{https://r4ds.had.co.nz/r-markdown.html}{here}. 

\paragraph{Assignment download, completion and submission.}

The following steps should be carried out for each homework assignment. Work through these steps for Homework 0.

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Download.} Homework assignments will be made available on the class Github repository (under the \href{https://github.com/Katsevich-Teaching/stat-471-fall-2021/tree/main/homework/}{homework} folder). To download the assignment, navigate to the \texttt{stat-471-fall-2021} directory on your computer in the Terminal (either through RStudio or a separate Terminal window), as in step 5 of the section ``Git and Github setup'' above. Then, pull the latest version of the class repository from Github by typing
<<eval=FALSE>>=
git pull
@  
\noindent If the repository has changed on Github and on your computer, then Git will automatically merge these two sets of changes. In this case, Git will automatically open an editor to allow you to type an informative message about this merge. However, a default message is already present and you do not need to change it, so simply close this editor. The default editor Git uses is Vim, and to close it you can type \texttt{:q} and then press enter. 
\textit{Note:} Other course materials (e.g. lecture notes) will also be distributed via the course Github. These materials should be downloaded using the same process as above.
\item \textbf{Complete.} Open RStudio. Navigate to the directory (e.g. \texttt{homework-0/}) containing the homework assignment in the files pane (Figure~\ref{fig:rstudio}E). Click \texttt{More} -> \texttt{Set As Working Directory} (Figure~\ref{fig:rstudio}D). Then, click on the Rmd file (e.g. \texttt{homework-0.Rmd}) to open it in the RStudio editor. Change ``FirstName LastName'' to your first and last name. Work through the problems in the assignment, keeping the problem statements as they are. When you make changes to the Rda file, click ``Knit'' near the top of the editor pane (Figure~\ref{fig:rstudio}A) to update the PDF output file. It is convenient to place the RStudio and PDF preview windows side by side. To save your work, periodically \textit{commit} it to Git by typing
<<eval=FALSE>>=
git add --all
git commit -m "[commit message briefly describing the changes]"
@  
at the Terminal. 
\item \textbf{Submit.} When you have completed your assignment, compile to PDF and commit one last time. Then, push the changes to your Github repository by typing the following command in the Terminal:
<<eval=FALSE>>=
git push
@
This will have the effect of synchronizing your files with your \textit{personal} Github repository (but not the class repository). Submit the compiled PDF to \href{https://www.gradescope.com/courses/285259}{Gradescope}. If you are unfamiliar with Gradescope, please watch \href{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oHvYPaYVhpo}{this brief video}.
\end{itemize}

